@antoniof my scripts are not generic. What files they work on and where output goes is hardcoded in the scripts. In a perfect world I'd have time and willingness to (learn to) make a program that lets me click a workflow together but here I need to get things done for my clients and so for new projects I just copy the scripts from best matching previous project and adjust them to fit. I put the scripts in the directory of the project.

Bash + zenity is one example. I also use Python for example. As you've noted it's not perfect but in lieu of a better tool it gets things done for me. I heavily rely on it for automating tasks for each project.

I'm not sure how Nautilus would know the script is created on this computer by this user. I get that asking "run in terminal" or "run" is confusing but I'm not sure always showing the terminal is a good case for say a script (Bash/Python/Ruby/whatever) with a GUI. Not every script with a GUI comes from a software repository or is nicely packaged with a .desktop file.

